        What Is a Price Guide and How Do Brisbane Agents Set One?
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        A price guide tells buyers what to expect to pay for a property. But how is it set, what are agents actually required to do, and what does it mean for you as a seller?
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Every property campaign in Brisbane involves a price guide in some form. Whether it is a specific figure, a range, or a "offers over" format, it signals to buyers where the seller and agent believe the property sits in the market. For sellers, understanding how a price guide is set and what obligations agents carry around it is important, because a guide that is out of step with reality will either leave money on the table or kill buyer interest before the campaign has a chance to run.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What a price guide actually is</h2>
      <p>A price guide is a publicly communicated expectation of what a property is likely to sell for. It is not the same as the reserve price in an auction campaign, which is private and set just before auction day. It is not the same as the asking price in a private treaty campaign, which is the listed price a vendor is prepared to accept offers around. A price guide is what buyers see in marketing, on real estate portals, and in conversations with the agent, and it shapes how many people inspect, whether they bother getting finance pre-approval, and how seriously they engage.</p>

      <p>In practice, price guides are used in different ways depending on the method of sale. For auction campaigns, a price guide is provided as a range and is updated as the campaign progresses and the level of buyer interest becomes clearer. For private treaty and expressions of interest campaigns, the listed asking price or price range serves the same function. In all cases, the guide is meant to reflect a genuine assessment of likely sale price, not a wishful or strategic anchor that bears no relationship to what a buyer would rationally pay.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How Brisbane agents set a price guide</h2>
      <p>A well-set price guide starts with comparable sales. The agent looks at what similar properties in the same suburb have sold for over the past six to twelve months, adjusting for differences in land size, dwelling size, condition, presentation, aspect, proximity to amenity, and any features that are unusual for the area. No two properties are identical, so the analysis involves judgment about which sales are genuinely comparable and how much weight to give each one.</p>

      <p>Market conditions at the time of listing matter significantly. If comparable sales from six months ago were achieved in a period of lower stock and strong buyer demand, and conditions have since softened, the agent needs to factor that in rather than anchoring mechanically to past figures. Days-on-market data is useful here: if comparable properties are now taking six weeks to sell instead of two, that suggests buyer conviction has cooled and the guide should reflect that shift.</p>

      <p>Vendor expectations also enter the picture, though they should not drive the guide. A common tension in the agent-vendor relationship is that vendors often have a figure in mind, informed by personal attachment, the cost of renovations, or hearsay from a neighbour's sale. A good agent will have an honest conversation about what the evidence actually supports, rather than overstating the likely outcome to win the listing. Overpricing at the outset is one of the most reliable predictors of a poor result: properties that sit on the market because they are pitched too high tend to accumulate days on market, attract reduced-price offers, and ultimately sell for less than they would have achieved with a realistic guide from day one.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Price guide, reserve, and asking price: the differences</h2>
      <p>These three terms are often conflated but serve distinct functions. The price guide is what is shared with buyers throughout a campaign. The reserve is the minimum a seller will accept at auction, set privately by the seller and their agent and not disclosed until bidding reaches it or passes it. The asking price applies in private treaty and is the published figure around which offers are invited.</p>

      <p>In an auction campaign, the relationship between the price guide and the reserve matters. A well-run campaign will have a reserve that sits within or just above the price guide range, informed by the buyer interest that has emerged during the campaign. Where agents can come unstuck is when the reserve is set significantly above the guide, meaning the property is passed in at auction and the vendor and agent then face the awkward position of negotiating post-auction at a price the guide never accurately signalled. Buyers who feel misled tend to walk, not negotiate.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Queensland rules on underquoting and agent obligations</h2>
      <p>Queensland has specific rules that govern how agents communicate price expectations to buyers. The Property Occupations Act 2014 prohibits agents from misleading prospective buyers about the likely selling price of a property. This includes setting a price guide that is significantly below what the agent genuinely believes the property will sell for, a practice known as underquoting.</p>

      <p>Underquoting is both an ethical problem and a legal one. It wastes buyers' time by bringing people into the process who cannot afford to compete at the actual sale price, and it erodes trust in the profession. In practice, Queensland's regulatory framework means agents have a positive obligation to form and communicate a genuine view of price, update their price guidance as the campaign progresses, and not advertise at figures that they know will not reflect the sale outcome.</p>

      <p>As a seller, this framework should give you confidence that your agent's price guide carries some weight. But it also means you should push back if you feel the guide your agent is proposing does not reflect what the evidence supports. Ask to see the comparable sales analysis. Ask what adjustments have been made and why. An agent who cannot clearly explain how they arrived at the guide is not doing the analytical work that underpins an accurate one.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How to assess whether your agent's price guide is realistic</h2>
      <p>Start by doing your own research on recent comparable sales in your suburb. CoreLogic, Domain, and realestate.com.au all provide sold price data. Look at properties that have sold in the past three to six months that share your land size, bedroom and bathroom configuration, and approximate standard of finish. Apply common sense adjustments for differences: a better aspect, a renovated kitchen, or a larger block all add to value, while dated fixtures, a busy road, or a smaller outdoor area subtract from it.</p>

      <p>Then compare what you find against your agent's guide. If the guide sits comfortably within the range of comparable sales and the agent can explain any differences clearly, that is a good sign. If the guide is materially above comparable evidence, ask the agent to show you the sales that justify the premium. If they cannot point to specific sales that support their figure, treat the guide with scepticism. A guide that flatters you at listing but does not hold up in the market will cost you time and very likely money.</p>

      <p>It is also worth asking your agent what will happen if the market response in the first two weeks does not support the guide. How will they approach a price adjustment, and at what point? Agents who have thought clearly about campaign management will have a view on this. Those who have not tend to let properties sit too long at the wrong price and then scramble to explain why a reduction is needed.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">When your expectations and the price guide do not align</h2>
      <p>If your expectation of your property's value and your agent's price guide are significantly different, do not assume the agent is being conservative to set up an easy result. But do not dismiss their analysis either. The most useful conversation you can have is to ask them to walk you through the comparable sales evidence and explain where they see your property sitting relative to those sales.</p>

      <p>If after that conversation you still disagree, you have a few options. You can get a second appraisal from another agent to see whether the views are consistent. You can commission an independent valuation, which carries more weight but costs money and takes time. Or you can list at a higher price and accept that your campaign may take longer to run. The risk of the third option is that a property that sits on the market accumulates a stigma that reduces buyer urgency and gives offers room to come in below where they would have if the guide had been right from the start.</p>

      <p>In Brisbane's inner-east market, where buyer pools are active but informed, an overpriced guide does not typically produce a higher result. It produces a longer campaign with more vendor anxiety and, often, a lower final price than an accurately guided campaign would have achieved from the outset.</p>

